these legacies, logics, and logistics) work in practice. Individual essays explore a number of topics—including time frames and the future, the use of percentages in observations and judgments, the explanation of prices, the coexistence of different world currencies, the reapplication of longtime economic theories in new settings, and, crucially, how we talk about the economy, how we use stable terms to describe a turbulent system. Valuable as standalone pieces, the essays build into a cogent method of economic anthropology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEconomic anthropologyzAfrica. 0aEconomic anthropology. 0aEconomics - History - 21st century. 0aEconomicsxHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  abusiness development, growth economics, anthropology, essays, essay collection, financial crisis, 2008, economic anthropologist, sociology, socio-historical approach, institutions, wealth, platform economy, military rule, nigeria, soft-currency economies, ethnography of price, logistics, food regulation, consumers, africa, african studies, theory, international trade, negotiations.1 aDenzer, LaRay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuyer, Jane I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226326900423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226326900/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles